# Executive Meeting
Frank G wants me to handle the Cox contract\.
2 lawsuits: 
1. Elderly couple \(Shaunessey?\) bought the unit sight\-unseen\. Long before they bough, there was a water leak that was repaired\. The new owner suspects water and mold problems\. There was an inspection and no mold was found\. Unit 1144\.
2. Unit 1101\. Water is seeping into a garage\. The lower unit owner is not there\. Plumbing of the upper unit was leaking between the floor and ceiling\.\. The unit was unoccupied for a long time\. It is not known how long the water was leaking\. The claim was denied because the unit was unoccupied for more than 14 days\.
3. Problem with Lobby’s place\. He owes the HOA over $13,000\. They want to settle for $12,000\. There’s a long history of L not paying and not doing required repairs\.
Our CCNR’s need to be updated\. $1,200 est\. to review\.
We are bound by an implied non\-disclosure because we are on the board\.

# Gothic Landscaping
Michelle, Morgan and Trevor\.
Michelle was promoted and will no longer be our rep\. Acct mgr will also be operations: Morgan\. M is 2 levels above the on\-site foreman\. They trim and clean 1/4 of the property each week\. Mow once per week\. They spray for weeds every time, as needed\. A full day is 7 hours\.  1/2 days are 3\.5 hours\.
Dan observes that they are never here until 3\.
Trevor offered to report hours to Jeff\. He also says that they use Paid Time Off on rains days\. There were at most 4 rain days last year\. Rain days are called for the entire valley\. 
Don stated that we want to be sure that we get the time we pay for\.
There is growth all year round\.
Frank said that the last 2 years, irrigation cost has gone down\.
They will only irrigate plants they put in\. Owners are not allowed to plant their own\.

# Suspicious Car
Monique from bldg 37 called to us because she saw a car with the motor running in the guest slot for bldg 36\. She said the car had been running since she first saw it at 4am\. The car was a gray VW Jetta\(?\) with blacked out windows and belongings stuffed in the front seat obscuring a view into the car\. We approached the car and a back window opened partly\. There was a man, dog and women in the back seat\. There was a bag of trash by the right side passenger door and a pad partly under the car\. The man in the car said there are waiting for their friends from the AirBnB, but didn’t say which building their friends were in\. We continued our walk and after a few minutes saw the car leaving\. Monique picked up the bag of trash after the car left\.

Lynn and I went to the Cox Store on Scottsdale Rd and Frank Lloyd Wright\. We talked to Erin about the problems when talking to Cox Phone Reps and with the extra $10 charge on our bills\.

Erin talked to the manager then told us that they knew about the problems and are working on it\. We are to tell our owners and residents to skip calling the Cox 800 number and to go directly to that store to get the right equipment\.

There will be the $10 charge on bills until Cox billing figures it out\.

Jeff H checked the Cox bill sent to FSI\. The bill reflects the new charge\.

# Cox
My bill came in at $122\.77 \(American Express Platinum\) which is $9\.82 too much\.

I called Cox and talked to Jerry\. She said that the extra is due to a charge for a DVR\. I told her that I got a DVR by mistake and brought it back the next day\. She then said that I would get a credit of $9\.82 on the next bill and the correct amount for bills going forward is $112\.95\.

entries.text:
# Lori Jacques
RE: Email of 5/28/21

I visited Lori on 5/29/21 at 4pm to discuss the incident that led to the email of 5/28/21\.

Lori’s TV Installation:
She has a fairly new LG smart TV connected to Cox bulk video via a Contour 2 box\. ​*The TV is also connected to Lori’s home WiFi system,*​ and she has an Apple TV\. The LG TV is connected to the Contour 2 box and Apple TV via HDMI\.

On May 28, Lori tried to connect to HBO Max using the Contour voice activation feature\. The LG TV reported to her that she was being directed to “another application\.” My interpretation is that the TV switched to an Internet connection\. She was directed to a screen asking her to sign\-on to HBO Max or to sign up for a subscription\. She chose to sign\-on using her personal Cox account, and a code was displayed on her TV with directions to a web site that she displayed on her iPhone\. She tried to enter the code with no success and after some confusing displays on her iPhone, a message was displayed stating that her account was locked\. I’m not sure how this happened, but by this time, she had stumbled onto a scammer’s web site\.

She was directed to call a number, and after a short conversation she became suspicious of the scammer due to his unreasonable demands\. For example, he asked for the name of her bank, and he demanded that she use software that would allow him to control her phone\. She then hung up on him\. She did not divulge any personal information, like credit card numbers or bank account numbers\.

My Recommendations:
I think that HBO Max is not  a regular cable channel and is available via the Internet\. Residents can access the Internet via smart TV’s,  an Apple TV, a Roku, or an Amazon Fire\. Residents should try to activate HBO Max using their Cox account, and they do not have to create a new account\. If this method does not work, they should not go to any web sites displayed on their TV, computer or personal device, nor should they call a phone number displayed this way\. They should call the Cox phone number from their Cox bill\.
